    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-02-18T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-02-18T09:00:00-05:00" n="862"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d862">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">833.5151/472: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Uruguay</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dawson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Montevideo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-02-18T11:00:00-03:00"
                            >February 18, 1938—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received February 18—10:45 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>18. According to unpublished information confirmed by the Bank of the Republic
                    import quotas of official exchange for the month of February have now been fixed
                    for 11 countries excluding the United <pb facs="0950" n="941" xml:id="pg_941"/>
                    States. Quota total 1,025,000 pounds of which 400,000 pounds are for Great
                    Britain. This refers only to official exchange and has no connection with
                    proposed allotments of free exchange referred to in the Consulate General’s
                    telegram of February 17, noon.<note n="58" xml:id="d862fn58">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Sent for Commerce in reply to Department’s telegram February 16, 5 p.m.<note
                        n="59" xml:id="d862fn59">This telegram read as follows: “Following from
                        Commerce: Reported that 2,000 pounds sterling allotted daily since February
                        15, for countries without quota covering merchandise now in customs house.
                        Cable confirmation or denial.” (833.5151/470a)</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Dawson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
